  "prompt": "If someone launders money, do they break the law?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often from activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or other crimes) appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This process disguises the illegal origins of the money.\n\nLaws against money laundering are in place to combat organized crime, terrorism financing, and corruption, and to maintain the integrity of financial systems. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and long prison sentences.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prohibited under the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986, among other laws. Similarly, many countries have their own legislation and are often part of international agreements and frameworks, such as those established by the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), to combat money laundering globally.",
